Closes #2759

Adds support for deserializing `to-one` and `to-many` relationships.

Fields are deserialized based on the value of the `many` attribute.  `id` and `type` values are required[1].  Supplied type values are validated against the `type_` attribute.  The `id` field can be validated by specifying additional validators on the `validate` attribute.

```json
// to-one
{"data": {"type": "comments", "id": "1"}}
// deserializes to
"1"

// to-many
{"data": [{"type": "comments", "id": "1"}]}
// deserializes to
["1"]
```

1. http://jsonapi.org/format/#document-resource-object-linkage

* new `response.splash_response_status` and `response.splash_response_headers` attributes
* use them to avoid handing 400 and 498 response codes from remote websites as they are returned by Splash (requires a proper Lua script);
* more tests

The current version of Pulp 3 status page /api/v3/status is returning the plugins
installed.

For example:

```json
"versions": [
        {
            "component": "pulpcore",
            "version": "3.0.0a1"
        },
        {
            "component": "pulp_file",
            "version": "0.0.1a1"
        }
    ]

```

Adjust the get_plugins function to make use of this feature.

- For the `write_copy` function the formatter should always write the data.
- Better debugging output for instruments being pickled

@unga @core

It would be awesome if I could do something like this in syncserver and get the 406-handling for free::

    @collection.get(accept="application/json")
    @collection.get(accept="application/newlines", renderer="newlines")
    def get_collection(request):
        return ["list", "of", "items"]

This *almost* works out of the box, but not quite.  Unfortunately cornice assumes that there's only a single view  definition for each HTTP method, e.g. when it uses self.definitions[request.method] to look up the kwargs.  This prevents using the full power of pyramid's view predicates when declaring services.

This patch offers one possible approach, by making self.definitions just a list of api_kwargs that were declared.  Not sure how that will interact with the auto-generated documentation though.
